“It’s not about being the best; it’s about being the choice people make again and again. Once we have captured every heart and mind, THEN can we rest on our laurels and choose greatness once more. Many fail to see this, Steve Jobs being the exception.



Is it fun? Is it ergonomic? Intuitive? Can I pull anyone from the street and have them enjoy the user experience before the question even enters their mind, like a foul smell: ‘What is this?’”



“When I speak of Steve Jobs, I ;don’t mean the actual person; it’s a cultural reference. We know Steve Jobs for what he was, and what he is in public memory. When I talk about Steve Jobs, I refer to a type: the man who understands that experience and fun come before the technology. Then, after the customer is won over, we can return to the delicious technicalities, specs, and late nights of programming.”





